sec.p:
Ethics approval was obtained from Western Institutional Review Board (WIRB). Caregivers of adolescents with Kabuki syndrome were primarily targeted for recruitment given the possibility of cognitive deficits seen in patients with Kabuki syndrome that could make it difficult for them to complete a lengthy online survey. A recruitment flyer was distributed via a clinical site (Johns Hopkins University) and advocacy groups (All Things Kabuki, Kabuki Syndrome Kids, and Kabuki Syndrome Network) using e‐mail and social media. Interested caregivers reached out and were screened for eligibility via telephone; if eligible, they received a link to an electronic consent and online survey administered using the SurveyMonkey platform. Eligibility criteria included:
Verbal consent to be screened over the phone;
≥18 years old;
Located in the United States (US) or Canada;
Able to identify how they learned about the survey;
Able to identify when their son or daughter was diagnosed with Kabuki syndrome;
Able to confirm their son or daughter had at least one of the five cardinal manifestations of Kabuki syndrome): unique facial features, skeletal deformities, fingerprint abnormalities, mild or moderate intellectual disability, and/or growth deficiencies;
Confirmation that they were able to read and complete an online survey in US English; and
Confirmation that they were willing and able to complete an online survey that took at least 45 min to complete.
